# Remove files and folders in the current directory
rm -rf * # This command removes all files and folders in the current directory. The "rm" command is used to remove files, and the "-rf" options are used to forcefully remove directories and their contents without prompting for confirmation. The "*" wildcard is used to specify all files and folders in the current directory. Be cautious when using this command, as it will permanently delete all files and folders without any confirmation.
rm -d foldername # This command removes an empty directory named "foldername". The "rm" command is used to remove files and directories, and the "-d" option is used to remove an empty directory. If the directory is not empty, you will need to use "rm -rf foldername" to forcefully remove it along with its contents. Be cautious when using "rm -rf", as it will permanently delete the directory and all of its contents without any confirmation.
rm filename # This command removes a file named "filename". The "rm" command is used to remove files, and you simply specify the name of the file you want to delete. Be cautious when using this command, as it will permanently delete the specified file without any confirmation. If you want to remove multiple files, you can specify them all in the command, such as "rm file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt". This will remove all three specified files at once.
rm -i filename # This command removes a file named "filename" with interactive mode enabled. The "rm" command is used to remove files, and the "-i" option prompts you for confirmation before deleting the specified file. When you run this command, it will ask you "rm: remove regular file 'filename'?" and you can respond with "y" (yes) to confirm the deletion or "n" (no) to cancel it. This provides an extra layer of safety to prevent accidental deletion of important files. You can also use "rm -i" with multiple files, such as "rm -i file1.txt file2.txt", and it will prompt you for confirmation for each file before deleting them.
rm -rf foldername # This command forcefully removes a directory named "foldername" along with all of its contents. The "rm" command is used to remove files and directories, and the "-rf" options are used to forcefully remove directories and their contents without prompting for confirmation. When you run this command, it will permanently delete the specified directory and all of its contents without any confirmation. Be cautious when using this command, as it can lead to data loss if you accidentally specify the wrong directory. Always double-check the directory name before running this command to ensure you are deleting the correct directory and its contents.
rm -r foldername # This command removes a directory named "foldername" along with all of its contents. The "rm" command is used to remove files and directories, and the "-r" option is used to recursively remove directories and their contents. When you run this command, it will permanently delete the specified directory and all of its contents without any confirmation. Be cautious when using this command, as it can lead to data loss if you accidentally specify the wrong directory. Always double-check the directory name before running this command to ensure you are deleting the correct directory and its contents.  
rm a b c # This command removes multiple files named "a", "b", and "c". The "rm" command is used to remove files, and you can specify multiple file names in the command to delete them all at once. Be cautious when using this command, as it will permanently delete the specified files without any confirmation. Always double-check the file names before running this command to ensure you are deleting the correct files.
rm -i a b c # This command removes multiple files named "a", "b", and "c" with interactive mode enabled. The "rm" command is used to remove files, and the "-i" option prompts you for confirmation before deleting each specified file. When you run this command, it will ask you "rm: remove regular file 'a'?" for each file, and you can respond with "y" (yes) to confirm the deletion or "n" (no) to cancel it. This provides an extra layer of safety to prevent accidental deletion of important files. Always double-check the file names before running this command to ensure you are deleting the correct files.   
# Caution: The "rm" command is powerful and can lead to data loss if used incorrectly. Always double-check the file or directory names before running the "rm" command, especially when using options like "-rf" that can delete directories and their contents without confirmation. Consider using "rm -i" for an extra layer of safety, as it prompts for confirmation before deleting each file or directory.
